Quote


Postby grabiner » Thu Jun 23, 2016 9:29 pm 
The regular annuity is not a good investment, because it is an after-tax variable annuity, invested in stocks.  (I couldn't see a description of exactly what the trust is invested in, but the 2007-2009 returns, in which the annuity lost half its value, imply a mostly-stock investment.)The problem with holding stocks in a variable annuity (or non-deductible IRA) is that the tax cost is usually increased compared to a taxable account.  The tax on gains is deferred, not eliminated, and when you do withdraw, any gains are taxed at your full tax rate.  If you invest in a stock index fund in a taxable account, you'll probably come out ahead; you pay tax on the stock dividends every year, but that is a small part of the return.  Most of the tax on gains is deferred until you sell, and that tax is at the lower capital-gains tax rate.The tax-sheltered annuity (open only for employees of educational institutions) is a better deal, as it is a pre-tax 403(b) plan; your contributions are deductible and withdrawals are fully taxable.  However, it has a disadvantage compared to other retirement plans which is specific to NJ.  NJ does not allow a deduction for contributions to 403(b) plans.  If you retire in NJ, you don't pay NJ tax on the amount that was non-deductible, since it was already taxed; if you retire in another state, you pay tax on the whole withdrawal.  Thus, while it is still a good investment, it's better to max out your Roth IRA first.
 David Grabiner


Top









